		<description><![CDATA[I had a chance earlier this week to visit and speak at Hacker School in New York. Hacker School is an amazing place, billed as a &#8220;retreat for programmers&#8221;, where a remarkable group of curious and self-motivated people from a wide range of backgrounds put their lives on hold for 12 weeks to gather with [...]]]></description>
				<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>
I had a chance earlier this week to visit and speak at <a href="http://www.hackerschool.com">Hacker School</a> in New York.  Hacker School is an amazing place, billed as a &#8220;retreat for programmers&#8221;, where a remarkable group of curious and self-motivated people from a wide range of backgrounds put their lives on hold for 12 weeks to gather with like-minded people to learn about programming and spend their evenings (and 21st birthday parties) hearing talks about computability!﻿
</p>
<p>
Slides and notes from my talk are here: <A href="http://www.cs.virginia.edu/~evans/talks/hackerschool/index.html"><em>What Every Hacker Should Know about Theory of Computation</em></a>.
</p>
<p><center><br />
<a href="http://instagram.com/p/uHLxDpm48u/"><img src="http://www.cs.virginia.edu/~evans/talks/hackerschool/hstalk.jpg" width=600 height=450"></a><br />
</center></p>
